  '  keying:               "per-session",           // opt-in — KEM amortized across sessionTtlMs',
  '  sessionTtlMs:         number,                  // default: 15 minutes (per-session only)',
  '  sessionMaxResponses:  number,                  // default: 1024 (per-session only)',
  '  sessionStore:         { get, set, delete },    // operator-supplied (b.cache-shaped) for cluster sharing',
  '  // ---- audit + observability ----',
  '  audit:                boolean,                 // default: true (false to suppress audit emits)',
  '  observability:        b.observability,         // optional — counters for sessions established / replay-rejected / expired / rotated',
  '  trustProxy:           boolean,                 // default: false — honour x-forwarded-for in audit ip field',
  '  maxDecryptedBytes:    number,                  // default: 4 MiB — parse-bomb defense',
  '}</code></pre>',
  '<p><code>b.middleware.apiEncrypt</code> end-to-end-encrypts request and response bodies between operator-controlled clients (mobile / desktop / service-to-service) and the framework. TLS protects the network hops; <code>apiEncrypt</code> protects the body through every internal cleartext segment (load balancer cleartext, sidecar proxy, log aggregator, APM tooling). Full envelope crypto detail at <a href="/crypto-vault#ecies">Crypto &amp; Vault → ECIES</a>: ML-KEM-1024 + P-384 ECDH hybrid → SHAKE256 KDF → XChaCha20-Poly1305. Replay defense is a 16-byte client nonce checked + inserted atomically against <code>nonceStore</code> within a configurable replay window.</p>',
  '<p><strong>Per-request keying (default):</strong> every request carries fresh KEM material (<code>_ek</code>) — strictly safer if the framework\'s session storage gets compromised. Each request stands alone; no session bookkeeping. The request body is <code>{ _ek, _ct, _ts, _nonce }</code>; the response body is <code>{ _ct }</code>.</p>',
  '<p><strong>Per-session keying (opt-in):</strong> the first request carries the full bootstrap envelope <code>{ _ek, _ct, _ts, _nonce, _sid, _ctr }</code> — server stores the session key keyed by sid. Subsequent requests omit <code>_ek</code> and <code>_nonce</code>, sending only <code>{ _ct, _ts, _sid, _ctr }</code> (the monotonic counter replaces the nonce for replay defense). The response carries <code>{ _ct, _sid, _ctr }</code> and the client validates the response counter is strictly increasing. Sessions expire on <code>sessionTtlMs</code> OR after <code>sessionMaxResponses</code> responses — server emits 401 with <code>session-expired</code> / <code>session-rotation-required</code> so the client re-bootstraps. <strong>The trade-off:</strong> per-session amortizes ~1.6 KB of KEM material across the session for high-throughput / mobile / metered-network apps, but a leaked session key exposes that session\'s traffic. Operators that can\'t afford a session-leak attack stay on per-request.</p>',
  '<p><strong>Operator-supplied <code>sessionStore</code>:</strong> defaults to an in-memory map for single-process apps. Multi-replica deploys pass a <code>{ get(sid), set(sid, row, opts?), delete(sid) }</code>-shaped handle — <code>b.cache.create({ backend: "cluster" })</code> is shape-compatible. The session row carries <code>{ sessionKey, lastReqCtr, responsesEmitted, createdAt, expiresAt, lastUsedAt }</code>; operators wiring an external store SHOULD seal the row via <code>b.vault.seal</code> at write time and unseal at read time so a leaked DB row doesn\'t leak the session key.</p>',
  '<pre><code class="language-javascript">// Per-request mode (default) — no behaviour change from v0.6.x.',
